snippet.textDisplay:
This is pretty misrepresented. On a fundamental level, the tech companies have simply created business segments that sell centralized computational power (Cloud computing) to the already heavily tech forward oil companies who have already gathered software to process the data they've already collected.

In many cases the cloud service options are identical to options offered to other industries, like healthcare.

The only real difference here is that instead of shell or exxon building massive data centers to process their data, they lease computer time from amazon, msft, and google's massive data centers.

I've simplified this pretty heavily, the whole situation is a big nothing burger here, but what else would you expect from vox?

snippet.textDisplay: I wish to give some perspective on machine learning. There is a chess AI named alpha0 which played against itself for 4 hours to learn the game, however these four hours aren't four hours for us because they can play 8000 games per second meaning that if you assume that a game will last about 7.5 minutes on average for humans playing in 5/5 speed chess then the AI amassed 1600 years of human experience in 4 hours. It is absolutely mind boggling.
